==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro}} {{term|avocat}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|advocatus|advocātus}}, past participle of {{term|advocare|advocāre|to call for}}.

===Pronunciation===
* Noun:
** {{enPR|ăd'vəkət}}, {{IPA|/ˈædvəkət/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/"{dv@k@t/}}, {{audio|en-us-advocate-noun.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* Verb:
** {{enPR|ăd'vəkāt}}, {{IPA|/ˈædvəkeɪt/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/"{dv@keIt/}}, {{audio|en-us-advocate-verb.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# Someone whose job is to speak for someone's case in a court of law; a [[counsel]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
# Anyone who argues the case of another; an [[intercessor]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#* '''c. 1591''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''Richard III'', First Folio 1623:
#*: I neuer did incense his Maiestie / Against the Duke of Clarence, but haue bin / An earnest '''aduocate''' to plead for him.
# A person who speaks in support of something. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}
#* '''2011''', Alix Lee, ''The Guardian'', 9 Oct 2011:
#*: He became a tireless '''advocate''' for the needs of adults with IMD throughout Britain and internationally.
# A person who supports others to make their voices heard, or ideally for them to speak up for themselves.
#: ''Since she started working with her '''advocate''', she has become much more confident.

